        <h3>Is talking over the phone actually helpful?</h3>
        <div>
          <p>
			University of Cambridge psychologists performed a research study with ~4,000 patients across ~190,000 therapy sessions in order to compare ‘over-the-telephone’ and ‘face-to-face’ therapy. Their findings were positive:</p>
			<br>

			<p style="font-weight: 600;">“We demonstrated that over-the-telephone and face-to-face showed equivalent effectiveness for anxiety symptoms, depression symptoms, and work and social functioning in all but the most severely affected patients”</p>
			<br>

			<p>So according to this study (as well as others), phone conversations can be quite helpful for emotional support. If you’re struggling with severe or extreme feelings though, you likely need more intensive, face-to-face resources for help. </p>
			<br>

			<p>If you’re skeptical, we suggest just giving it a try. At the least, you can see what talking to a peer counselor is like, and decide after if you’d prefer other options.</p>
			<br>

			<p>If you’d like to read the quoted study, please <a style="font-weight: 600" href="http://www.plosone.org/article/fetchObject.action?uri=info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0042916&representation=PDF" target="_blank">click here.</a></p>
            
          </p>
        </div>
